                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Marginalia:</label> Many notes, amendments, and comments written by
                        <persName role="pat fmo ins" key="person_102326800"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/102326800/">Sir William Jones</persName>.
                        <lb/><label>Inscriptions:</label><list rend="bulleted">
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> signed <q xml:lang="en">SH
                              Lewin from Sir W<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> Jones's Collection
                                 <date>1831</date></q> by former owner <persName role="fmo ato ins"
                              key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne Lewin</persName>. </item>
                        <item> The <locus from="viib" to="viib">first left flyleaf b side (f.
                              ib)</locus> bears a list by Jones:<lb/><list rend="numbered">
                              <item>A Description of Select Indian Plants.</item>
                              <item>On the Acient Kinds of Magadha</item>
                              <item>On the Primitive Religion of the Hindu.</item>
                              <item>Arimadversious) On the Brahmanical System of Paoline</item>
                           </list>
                        </item>
                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label> The <locus from="Inner_back_cover"
                        to="Inner_back_cover">left pastedown</locus>: <q xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca
                        Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q xml:lang="en">2/E</q>, and <q
                        xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough">Bland</hi> MSS No. <hi
                           rend="strikethrough">408</hi></q> with the name and number crossed out
                     and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en">187</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Bound in a late-18th century European style binding for Jones.</p>
                        <p>Sewn on five cords, with three laced into the
                              <material>pasteboards</material>. Edges trimmed and coloured yellow,
                           then decorative front-bead endbands sewn in white and blue threads at
                              <locus from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail"
                              to="Tail">tail</locus> in red and white <material>silk</material>
                           threads. Covered in full diced Russia calfskin
                              <material>leather</material>, with five raised bands.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Spine panels palleted with a dotted lines with
                           single lines either side. Septfoils in the centres, and palmette corners.
                           Board margins bear decorative rope designs, outlined with single fillets
                           on either side, with thick-and-thin diagonal lines on the board edges. </decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>265</height>
                              <width>213</width>
                              <depth>29</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair condition, with joints
                           cracked, tailcap missing, headcap torn, endbands broken, and exteriors
                           abraded. Boards yawning at the fore-edge. Boxed.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed by <persName role="scr" key="person_f7930">Bahman, son
                        of Bahman, son of Isfandiyar (d. 1788)</persName> for <persName role="pat"
                        key="person_102326800" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/102326800/">Sir William
                        Jones (1746–1794)</persName> in <origPlace
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7030776">Calcutta
                     (Kolkata)</origPlace>; undated, but between <date cert="high"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" from="1784" to="1788-08-05">1783, when Jones' arrived,
                        and when Bahman passed away in 1788</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Jones death, his wife <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/3241569" key="person_3241569">Lady Anna Maria
                           Jones (1748–1829)</persName> inherited the volume, then after her death,
                        the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/64237639/" key="person_64237639">R. H. Evans
                           (1778–1857)</persName> sold it on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1831-05-20">20 May 1831</date> (lot 433), to bookseller <persName
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/69276015/" key="person_69276015"
                           >John George Cochrane (1781–1852)</persName>, who likely acted as an
                        agent on behalf of Chancery Court Clerk and Royal Asiatic Society member
                           <persName role="fmo ato ins" key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne Lewin
                           (1795–1840)</persName>, for whom he evidently also obtained other
                        ex-Jones volumes (e.g. Rylands <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6667"><idno>Persian
                              MS 187</idno></ref> and <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6725">240</ref>;
                        see Lawrence, 'Building a Library', pp. 34, 70, Appendix 3).</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Lewin's death, his family evidently sold his manuscripts, largely then
                        obtained by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866-06">June, 1866</date>, paid in two
                        instalments of £450 and £400, and then moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
